{
  "texts": [
    "In the context of taste, this can involve optimizing ingredient combinations to achieve desired flavor profiles, nutritional constraints, or consumer preferences.",
    "For example, an RL framework could iteratively adjust ingredient ratios in a virtual formulation, receiving feedback from predictive taste models or consumer preference simulators as reward signals.",
    "This method supports automated recipe generation and can reduce reliance on costly physical testing.",
    "As a growing frontier, RL complements other AI techniques by offering an adaptive approach to complex taste design problems.",
    "In contrast, unsupervised learning techniques, such as K-means and hierarchical clustering, reveal natural groupings within taste data, enabling targeted product development strategies based on unique flavor profiles (Shawky et al. 2024)."
  ]
}